title: For Sale:  Engraved W & C Scott & Son Model “The Premier” Double Barrel SxS Shotgun 30”, Crystal Indicators MFD 1878-1887 Antique, Cased & Accessories 10 Gauge
postcontent: his is a 10 gauge double barreled shotgun by W.C. Scott & Sons of England. It was made sometime between 1878 and 1887 as judged by the patent dates and “NOT FOR BALL” markings. This gun was among the maker's best offerings of the era, boasting highly figured wood with a buffalo horn buttplate and very detailed and elaborate engraving that you just don’t see on guns made today, even by custom shops. PLEASE SEE OUR PICTURES!! The design includes “Crystal” loaded chamber indicators, extractors and an automatic safety. The barrels are blue, and we believe they have been refinished. The case colored finish on the receiver and the finish on the wood are original. The shotgun has about 92% of its current metal finish remaining. There are a few light marks in the barrels and the receiver’s case coloring is somewhat muted. There are also a few light marks in the stocks. The bores are bright but show extremely light erosion at the muzzles and in spots scattered throughout. What is really impressive about this shotgun is the fine detailing of the engraving – there is more engraving on the trigger guard than most modern high grades have in total. If you have been looking for a vintage English shotgun to collect, with engraving details that will amaze, then look no further. It even comes with its original fitted factory case that has the original certificate of proofing from W.C. Scott & Sons signed and with the serial number of this shotgun, along with cleaning accessories, tools and spare parts.

title: For Sale:  CZ-75 Pre B
postcontent: For sale is my CZ-75 Pre B model that appears to have been manufactured in 1967. The CZ is one of the most respected 9mm pistols ever. This is the Pre-B model and has a thumb safety to allow for carrying "cocked and locked." The pistol runs flawlessly but it does have a few cosmetic blemishes, most of which are from holster wear. it won't win any beauty contests but it's definitely a shooter. The CZ would make a great pistol for anyone holding or seeking a Tennessee carry permit. Although I have no concrete proof of it, this appears to be Czech police trade in. The pistol comes with a Bladetech belt holster and four magazines: two CZ mags and two Mec-Gar mags. The Mec-Gars are 17 and 19 round magazines, which is quite a bit of firepower for a service pistol. Thanks for looking.
